metadata.value: The black Orang-outang of Africa (Simia Niger); The red or Asiatic Orang-outang (Simia Satyrus). Figure 1 and 3 (of red Orang-outang) are original drawings from nature by Howitt. Engraved by W.H. Lizars. Information text James Wilson: This red Orang-outang was brought to UK on return of embassy to China. Monkey died after arival in UK. Sent to Museum by the late Marquis of Hastings and labelled 'Head of the red Orang-outang from Borneo'. Remark Dr Knox (friend of Wilson): 'The cranium of a young Orang and an adult one is not known yet in Europe'.

Information text James Wilson: Figure on plate is drawn from a full grown female Water Hog which lived for some months in Liverpool. metadata.value: The Great White Dolphin (Beluga). Drawn by Patrick Syme and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Information text James Wilson: For three months in 1815 a White Whale was observed to inhabit the Firth ('Frith') of Forth. It was killed in a river near Stirling. Purchased by Mr Robert Bald of Alloa, and kindly transmitted to Professor Jameson ('the Beluga of scientists'). The number of this animal annually killed is great (in 4 years 3508 by British Greenland Ships).

metadata.value: The Finch Falcon of Bengal. Drawn by James Wilson and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: M. Temminck has given a representation of it and it is also figured in Mr Horsfield's Zoological Researches, though neither has succeeded in conveying a true idea of the peculiar elegance of the bird in question. With the hope of effecting this as well as to exhibit the species in a state of plumage in which it has not yet publicly appeared, I have added Plate 2 to the general stock. James Wilson in note: My intelligent friend Mr Audubon of Louisiana, whose magnificent collection of ornithological drawings has lately excited such general interest in Edinburgh, has communicated to me a singular fact...

metadata.value: Brisbane's Promerops (Epimachus Brisbanii). Drawn by James Wilson and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Text James Wilson: These specimens were sent to the Edinburgh Museum early in the year 1824 from New Holland, by Sir Thomas Brisbane, in honour of whom the species was then named. In the MS Catalogue which accompanied them (1823) figure 1 was marked 'Number 30, Velvet Bird, rare'. This specimen was shot at Port Macquarrie. Figure 2 is supposed to be female.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Ternate King-Fisher (Tanysiptera Dea). Drawn by James Wilson and engraved bu W.H. Lizars. Text James Wilson: Specimen in Edinburgh Museum. The figure on plate is of size of life. Like Birds of Paradise highly prized for its beauty and frequently mutilated by the natives, deprived both of legs and wings. In Edinburgh specimen the feet are very similar to those of other King-Fishers.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Quezal or Golden Trogun (Trogon Pavoninus). Drawn from nature by James Wilson and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: I believe the first specimens ever seen in this country were lately brought from Central America by J.C. Schenley, Esq. who obtained them in the course of his diplomatic mission, and kindly transmitted one to the Edinburgh Museum. Owing to the great extent of the two central feathers of the upper coverts of the tail, I have been obliged to reduce the figure on the plate to one-half of the natural size
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Aldrovandine Peacock (Pavo Aldrovandi, adult male). Drawn by James Wilson, engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: At the time the work just quoted was published, no example of this species was to be found in any collection in Europe. It now exists in the Paris collection; and through the exertions of Professor Jameson, two specimens were obtained for the rich ornithological Museum of Edinburgh during the summer of 1822. Both of these are male birds; one is in perfect adult plumage, the other is young and immature. The original specimens in the Museum are furnished with long spurs. James Wilson in note: I have therefore adopted the name by which this rare and hitherto imperfectly known bird has been designed for years in the Edinburgh Museum, in honour of the author who first wrote about it, Ulysses Aldrovandus of Bologna.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: Sabine's Gull (Larus Sabini). Drawn by James Wilson and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson in note: On introducing for the first time into this pages the name of the venerable Bewick, I cannot refrain from a brief expression of high estimation in which I hold the talents of that unrivalled artists, and most intelligent observer of nature. His engravings on wood of the British Birds are distinguished by a force and truth of character, and a felicity of expression which have neither been equalled nor approached in any other work of natural history.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: Ross's Gull (Larus Rossii). Drawn by James Wilson and engraved by W.H. Lizars. James Wilson: The individual now represented, being the only specimen of the bird known to exist in any collection... James Wilson in note: My reasons for having adopted the name of Ross's Gull, rather than that of Roseater Gull, under which the species in question is described in the first Part of the valuable work above referred to, are shortly these: When the skin (which the Museum owns to the attention of Lord Melville) was first brought to Edinburgh by Dr Richardson, the intrepid and intelligent traveller, I had the pleasure of immediately examining it at the house of that gentleman, in company with Professor Jameson. Dr Richardson, who was at this time (winter 1823-4) occupied in arranging and describing various arctic animals, proposed that this unique specimen should be named, in honour of Lieutenant Ross, the gentleman by whom the bird was shot... In the mean time, Professor's assistant in the Museum, Mr MacGillivray probably not aware of Dr Richardson's intentions, labelled the bird at interim Roseate Gull. It was under this latter name, that Sir William Jardine first saw the specimen consigned to my hands to make the drawing from which the annexed plate is engraved; and as it fell to my lot to be the first to figure it, I considered it as due to Dr Richardson to retain the name which he had previously (though) privately imposed.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: Jameson's Gull (Larus Jameson II). Drawn by James Wilson an engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: The gull was brought to Leith by one of the Australian ships from the shores of New Holland. I am unable to indicate its locality with greater precision, nor am I acquainted with any of the particulars of its history. It appears to be an undescribed species, and I have named it in honour of Professor Jameson, to whose exertions we already owe so many novelties in every branch of zoological science. The specimen is now in the Edinburgh Museum.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Great Auk (Alca Impennis). Drawn by W.B. Hawkins and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation text James Wilson: Professor Jameson informs me, that, not long since, a dead specimen was picked up floating in the sea off the Isle of Sundy, on the coast of south Devon. The specimen figured on this plate was obtained by Mr Bullock. It is now in the British Museum; and I am indebted for the drawing from which the engraving was executed to the kindness of my valued correspondent J.G. Children, Esq. F.R.S. & C.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Guardenian Siren (Siren Lacertins). Drawn from life by Patrick Syme and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: I have therefore presumed to name it the Gardenian Siren, in remembrance of Dr. Garden, by whom the animal appears to have been first observed. For the accurate drawing engraved on this plate I have to acknowledge my obligation to Mr Patrick Syme of Edinburgh, to whose friendship I stand indebted for much valuable assistance and advice during the progress of this work.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: Text about Reptiles related to Plate 24 (the Gardenian Siren).
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: The Foliated Pipe-Fish (Hippocampus Foliatus). Drawn by W. Thomson, Hobart Town and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Text James Wilson: The specimen here figured was sent to Professor Jameson from Van Dieman's Land. It was accompanied by a very beautiful and highly detailed drawing, taken soon after death by Mr William Thomson of Hobart Town. From Mr Thomson's drawing this plate is engraved. I previously compared the drawing with the animal itself and found it perfectly correct. The representation is of exact size of nature, and supersedes the necessity of a detailed description. Allied to hippocampus (sea-horse). In the dried specimens the head is usually at right angles with the body, the thorax is curved, and the tail turned upwards. From the peculiar aspect which they exhibit in this condition, they have received the name sea-horse.
metadata.label: Repro Description

metadata.value: Nicols Cone (Conus Nicolii). Drawn and engraved by W.H. Lizars. Quotation James Wilson: I have named it in honour of its owner Mr William Nicol in Edinburgh, whose extensive and well chosen collection of shells has ever been open to the inspection of the curious, and whose scientific knowledge in conchology, as well as in other departments of natural history, is worth a tribute, which I should not have thought of paying to the mere possessor of a unique specimen.
metadata.label: Repro Description

Case-Nuove of Lyons, by whom it was bred from the larva. James Wilson concerning insects: Even in our country, where natural history is so sparingly patronized, and so slightly valued, this beautiful branch of zoology has been rather sumptuously exhibited, and the names of... will be readily present themselves to the recollection of the reader.
